<subSubSection id="F8F90BC7FFF7FFC76BC75D40FE18FEC0" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="12" pageNumber="11" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="B05C584CFFF7FFC76BC75D40FE18FEC0" blockId="12.[192,1440,1872,1928]" lastBlockId="14.[192,1440,217,339]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis id="8297845EFFF7FFC56BC75D40FEAFF8FB" bold="true" box="[192,338,1872,1896]" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Females can be diagnosed by lacking integumental markings on 
<collectionCode id="D6F2C089FFF7FFC56FAE5D40FB40F8FB" box="[1193,1213,1872,1896]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="12" pageNumber="11">T</collectionCode>
2, the presence of contrasting patterns of black and white setae, head unarmed posterolaterally, genal carina absent or weakly defined, mesosoma compact, scutellar scale and anterior transverse carina present, mid and hind femora rounded apically, and pygidium broadly ovate. Males can be diagnosed by having the pygidium with a raised medial plate surrounded by lateral carinae and the head having a pair of blunt tooth-like projections on the front.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
